My curiosity about language was ignited when I took my first French class, after
moving to Canada for high school.
Since then, studying linguistics has been like a treasure hunt, allowing me to
discover bits and pieces of hidden knowledge about languages I thought I knew
so well as well as languages I had no idea existed.
Now, after dedicating four and a half years of my undergrad to
studying linguistics along with my other passion, computer science, I have made
the decision to pursue a graduate degree in linguistics in order to make my own
contributions to the field.

While I am keen to solve many of linguistics' unsolved problems, the one question
that motivates me most is _Why do the outcomes of language acquisition differ so
significantly between adults and young children?_
In other words, I am interested especially in problems concerning
individual differences in _ultimate attainment_ of linguistic competence.
The reason that I developed such a strong interest is surprisingly simple --- having
successfully acquired English and French as second languages,
I have always wondered what made my experience different from many others,
who may have just as much aspiration to learn a language well but still seem
unable to go beyond a certain glass ceiling.

Understanding ultimate attainment may be my "ultimate" goal, but our collective
knowledge of language acquisition is not nearly established enough to propose an
adequate unified theory.
Advancing our understanding of individual factors underlying successful second
language acquisition
is precisely the reason why I conducted the independent research project on
language aptitude and L2 French pronunciation, and why I am proposing the current
research project extending the scope to domain-general cognitive abilities,
Compared to my undergrad, I now have more direct access to the expertise and
support of faculty members and fellow colleagues as a Master's student at
McGill.
Furthermore, being immersed in a French milieu, I am able to connect much more
easily with researchers working actively on the acquisition of French as a
second language.
In fact, thanks to the Autorisation d'études hors établissement (AEHE),
I was able to enrol in a course at UQÀM, LIN8225: Acquisition des langues secondes.
Professeure Daphnée Simard, who is teaching the course, is a prolific L2 researcher
with two decades of experience on cognitive individual differences.
She and I have collaborated before on incorporating working memory into my project,
and she has expressed interest in supervising me for a PhD at UQÀM.

Once I complete my Master's degree, I plan to take advantage of the interdisciplinary
nature of my academic training, i.e. theoretical linguistics, language acquisition,
language teaching, and computer science, and continue my academic career bridging
these fields through a PhD program in applied linguistics.
The program at UQÀM, as well as similar programs at several Quebec
universities, will be among my top choices.